title: For Sale:  Custom built LONG STROKE piston AR upper receiver
postcontent:
Custom built LONG STROKE piston AR upper receiver.
I had this long stroke piston upper built because I could not afforded the over priced long stroke piston available on the market today ($2500.00 to $3000.00)
I have never had the chance to shoot it and now due to financial needs I have to let it go.
I am asking what I paid (1500.00) or best offer.

2 types of pistons are available from manufactures, long and short stroke.

Shot stroke pistons are more common because they are cheaper to produce. 
Ruger, Sig, S&W, ect. All produce short stroke piston because it is easier and cheaper for them to do so. 

Why a long stroke? A Long stroke piston cost more money but are a better system. The long stroke piston is the same system that the AK47 utilizes. A low-pressure, long-stroke gas piston design keeps from "hammering" the bolt as the short stroke designs do. By slowing down the acceleration of the bolt mass instead accelerated it over a greater distance. The result is less shock forces on the system, longer lasting parts and reliable feeding. It's the difference between unlocking your bolt with a ball peen hammer or accelerating it on a cushion of air!

The only companies that I am aware of that produce long stroke pistons are POF and LWRC although there may be others. Both of these companies charge well over $2500.00 for there long stroke pistons which is why I had mine built.  

This Long Stroke gas piston system is rated at a 1,000,000 compressions cycles allowing it to out live the life of the rifle itself.

 With the DeSantis Thumb Break Scabbard, the firearm rides high and is presented at an optimum draw angle. postcontent:
Up for sale is a 2011 Kahr PM9 (Polymer Micro - chambered in 9mm) I bought this firearm last March (2011) and for some time it has been my "go-to" carry gun due to how comfortable, accurate, and most importantly-reliable it is. I almost don't want to get rid of it, but I am finding that I typically would rather either carry a larger handgun if I am wearing a coat, or pocket-carry my smaller Bodyguard 380 if it is warmer weather. The PM9 is somewhere inbetween my S&W M&P Compact and the Bodyguard 380 (huge range, I know).

The gun has approximately 500-600 rounds of various ammo through it, includes the original plastic case, and has been taken very good care of (stored properly, cleaned after/before shooting, lubricated well, etc.)

With standard sights the gun retails (used) for approximately ~$495-$600, and this one is equipt with brand-new XS BIG DOT 24/7 Night Sights (tritium inserts in for front and rear sights) (~$120) (the original sights will also be included) and also has an in-the-waistband Don Hume holster (~$30) (shown in the pictures), as well as 2 extra magazines one-6 round and one-7 round (~$40 each). Additionally I will be willing to include an outside the waistband (Black) DeSantis leather holster with thumb-break (~$55)(not shown in picture).

I believe $550 is a fair price for the firearm and all the extras, or $575 without the DeSantis holster. Face to face sales ONLY and ONLY TO NEW YORK STATE Pistol Permit Holders. (I have my permit in Ontario County)

Please contact me if interested or if you have any questions or would like to make an offer. Thank you for looking!

The Pardus features many of the same components that have made the DPMS line of rifles successful, such as the forged 7075-T6 aluminum lower receiver, .223 caliber chambering and the outstanding accuracy and reliability of every DPMS rifle, but the new rifle will be a smaller, sleeker version of the traditional Panther rifle.
